  +section('9. Popina Island (98 ha)')
    .en
      h1 Popina Island (98 ha)
      p 
        stong Popina Island (98 ha) 
        |is a remaining calcareous erosion from the North-Dobrogea area, located in the North of Razim Lake, on the northern side, close to Iazurile and Sarinasuf fishing ponds and Iazurile village, having an altitude of 47 meters. Due to the continental semi-arid temperate climate, the xerophile vegetation and fauna reflects the steppe conditions, excepting the sea shore/low profile land, where the lake vegetation can be found. Here, some priority habitats were identified: gypsophile iberic vegetation (code 1520); natural eutrophic lakes with 
        em Magnopotamion 
        |or 
        em Hydrocharition 
        |type vegetation (code 3150) and annual colonization with 
        em Salicornia 
        |or other species of muddy and sandy areas (code 1310). Here, 300 species of superior plants were identified, from which two of them are common species: 
        em Euphorbia agraria 
        |and 
        em Euphorbia senguieriana
        |, and 
        em Ornithogalum oreoides
        |, endemic species. Among the identified plants, 38 species were signaled for the first time on RBDD territory, after 1990. Regarding the fauna, 200 species of insects were identified, three of them being described for the first time: 
        em Isophya dobrogensis
        |, 
        em Homorosoma validirostris
        |, 
        em Lixus scabricornis
        |. On the rocky cliff, Popina island accommodates a large population of  Dice Snake (
        em Natrix tessellata
        |), and among the 130 species of birds, 17 are nesting here, in the loess shore. In spring, when the vegetation is poor and small, swamp birds can be found (
        em Congolese wagtails
        |), forest birds: the Nightingale (
        em Luscinia megarhynchos
        |), Black-headed Bunting (
        em Emberiza melanocephala
        |), Calandra Lark (
        em Melanocorhypha colandro
        |) etc. The slight mezothermal springs which are on the northern side of the island (not studied yet) gives a more scientific interest to the island. The fauna of invertebrates (the same, not enough studied) has rarities like venomous spider  "Black Widow" (
        em Lactrodextra
        |) and the giant myriapod (
        em Scolopendra cingulata
        |). The Popina island constitutes an important stop for migratory birds: Shelduck (
        em Tadorna tadorna
        |) and Kestrel (
        em Falco tinnunculus
        |).
